here&#39;s an alternative (i.e. a non-jq) solution to the OP&#39;s query: the request was to remove all the entries in all the second level (from root) iterables except the last two.

Using [**`jtc`**](https://github.com/ldn-softdev/jtc), then the easiest way (and the most concise) is to _walk_ all the unwanted entries and purge them:
```
bash $ &lt;input.json jtc -w[:][:-2] -p
{
   &quot;bar&quot;: {
      &quot;ghi&quot;: {
         &quot;key1&quot;: &quot;value1&quot;
      }
   },
   &quot;foo&quot;: {
      &quot;efg&quot;: {
         &quot;key1&quot;: &quot;value1&quot;
      },
      &quot;fgh&quot;: {
         &quot;key1&quot;: &quot;value1&quot;
      }
   },
   &quot;qux&quot;: {
      &quot;jkl&quot;: {
         &quot;key1&quot;: &quot;value1&quot;
      },
      &quot;klm&quot;: {
         &quot;key1&quot;: &quot;value1&quot;
      }
   }
}
```

The _walk-path_ (`[:][:-2]`) is rather trivial here:  
\- `[:]` will iterate over all JSON nodes in the top (root) iterable (i.e. iterate over `bar`, `foo`, `qux` elements)  
\- `[:-2]` will iterate over each iterated (in the previous lexeme) iterable starting from the first until (but not inclusive) second from the end (e.g.: `foo`&#39;s object will be iterated `abc` thru `def` only, etc).  
_Note: The range select notation in `jtc` is pretty much the same like in Python._

Then `-p` instructs to purge all the completed walks, effectively leaving the original JSON structure and those elements which were not walked - that facilitates the query.

(PS. I&#39;m a developer of `jtc` the unix tool for JSON processing).

